Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany
Audit report
Preface
Taxes are the main source of revenue for public budgets.
A focus of the activities of the courts of auditors should therefore be on the examination of this area.
This applies in particular to sales tax fraud.
This alone results in annual tax losses of an estimated 100 billion Euro 1 in the European Union.
Already at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn in 2005, the participants pointed out the need for increased cooperation.
This makes it possible for the audit courts, for example, to exchange audit approaches and optimise audit practice.
VAT is particularly suitable for cooperation, as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, for the first time, the courts of auditors of both states were conducting parallel audits in the area of the VAT.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
Since the VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, it requires close cooperation between the courts of auditors, so that it can be fully assessed whether the measures taken are capable of countering the VAT fraud effectively.
The two courts of auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Management of the sales tax in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany Report on the audit
1. Introduction
Exam number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject of examination: (CZ) Administration of the USt (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter "NK"), audit
Objective of the examination:
(CZ) the administration of the VAT and the treatment of selected transactions between businessmen of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures applied by the tax authorities in the case of inter-governmental administrative assistance should be investigated.
(D) The audit should evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the auditors.
In addition, other fields of examination - linked to the VAT - should be worked on.
The findings made here should be compared in order to determine whether the taxation procedures can be optimised.
The period of examination was from 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the examination period to the completion of the exam.
2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on an audit of the administration of the VAT.
During the previous parallel investigation, they had uncovered suspected cases of intra-Community transactions,
Which made it seem appropriate to take another exam.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two audit courts made recommendations for the administration of the VAT.
The aim of the inspection was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and to investigate the suspected cases identified.
The audit also looked at other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in recovering VAT receivables, and the VAT audit of large companies.
The Court of Auditors has found that:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit
• Recommendation 1: The rules for registering taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU
In the first audit, the Court of Auditors compared the VAT registration procedures in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The Court therefore recommended harmonizing the registration of taxpayers within the EU.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of persons subject to VAT.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.
The Court of Auditors expected the Member States to agree on appropriate rules to remove unreliable operators from the VAT system as soon as possible, in accordance with its decision of principle.
The Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN on the final version of the draft.
The above-mentioned common rules are no longer included in it, and the two courts of auditors regret this.
They still consider such regulations important in order to prevent sales tax fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of Comprehensive Notices As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended that Member States submit Comprehensive Notices (ZM) on a monthly basis in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed more closely.
Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common system of value added tax for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for the submission of the ZM to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT law, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the implementation did not come into effect until 1 July 2010, which means that the obligation to submit the ZM on a monthly basis has not been transposed into national law on time.
• Recommendation 3: Data comparison of the VAT pre-registration and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the amalgamation of procedures for VAT pre-registration and ZM. The German financial administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Audit Office and set up a working group to work out possible solutions.
The work is not yet complete.
The Federal Audit Office will monitor the further development.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level In the course of the first audit, the two courts agreed that an effective risk management system could not be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States use different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU reviewed the system of information exchange within the EU - Eurocanet, while the Federal Audit Office focused on German participation in the "Risk Management Platform."
2. Control of selected intra-Community transactions
During the first audit, the courts of auditors had jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or which had been declared differently by the taxpayers of the two States in the VAT pre-applications (or UST declarations) or ZM.
The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community goods deliveries between the CZ and Germany for the inspection.
The audits by the tax authorities of both states were not yet completed when the first parallel audit was completed.
The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed, and the respective financial administrations have taken appropriate measures to this end (e.g. subsequent VAT requirements or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
3. Examination of selected, particularly high-risk intra-Community transactions
Also included in the audit were high-risk intra-EU transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by the Eurocanet system.
Eurocanet is designed to detect high-risk taxpayers.
Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in Eurocanet. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of Eurocanet.
From the point of view of an active participant state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained on which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as high-risk cases.
The NKU identified normal transactions as well as those suspected of fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected transactions.
High-risk transactions were only able to be checked to a limited extent, especially in the case of so-called "missing traders," whereby a check of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxable person.
Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
It is recommended that the customs and tax authorities work more closely together in order to be able to monitor the integrity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the end customer.
Germany and a number of other countries have refused to participate actively in Eurocanet, because they do not consider that there is a sufficient legal basis.
The Federal Audit Office found that the German financial administration uses other tools to identify high-risk taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
Created by the EUROFISC.
The experience gained so far with Eurocanet should be incorporated into the planned network for the fight against VAT fraud.
4.Mutual mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
That is why requests for intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are being dealt with in the same way.
The Federal Audit Office and NKU compared the statistics that both Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained discrepancies.
The two courts of auditors consider it useful to discuss the statistics again at EU level in order to avoid any remaining discrepancies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should include more information on the VAT.
Analysing detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both courts consider that Member States with a low recovery rate should try to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should support the Member States in this, if it so wishes.
5. UST test at large companies
The Court of Auditors analysed the legal situation regarding the VAT audit of large companies in both states.
In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the financial administrations that they considered important in this context.
At the same time, it became clear that the situation in both states is different.
For the selection of risk-related cases, the CZ has a system that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data, and profit and loss accounts).
Overall, the UST control can thus be effectively controlled and analysed.
A special finance office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.
In Germany, there is still no comparable system, which makes it more difficult to control and analyse the overall VAT control.
The German financial administration is more focused on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the VAT or VAT declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the analysis of this data.
