4. Examination of the management of sales tax in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint audit
4.1.1 Implementation of recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for registration of taxpayers within the EU
Based on the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended adapting the requirements for VAT registration and introducing new rules for deleting registration in the CZ.
These amended rules should more effectively reduce the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the VAT registration of taxable persons was not deleted if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech law no. 235 / 2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT law").
To date, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted any amendment to require the tax authorities to delete the tax if the taxable persons repeatedly do not file VAT declarations.
According to the Czech VAT law, the FA can delete ex officio the registration of a taxable person if a) the taxable person has not made any transactions for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for doing so; b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under the VAT law; c) the taxable person no longer meets the requirements for the duty of taxation.
The first examination had shown that, due to the existing legal situation, the Prague 1 FA had to delete the VAT registration of "foreign taxpayers" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year, if they were not obliged to register and pay VAT in the current calendar year.
The Prague 1 FA often did not delete the VAT registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be properly implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment of the VAT law, which came into effect on 1 January 2009.
According to this, the FA is authorised to delete the registration of a foreign taxable person if in the previous calendar year he did not provide taxable or exempt goods or services with the right to deduct VAT.
Recommendation 2
Monthly payment of the ZM
On the basis of the initial audit, the Court of Auditors had recommended that the monthly levy of ZM be introduced.
The Council's directive, which shortened the time limit for the ZM to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the VAT law, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, an ZM must be issued if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) VAT law are provided for a person registered as subject to VAT in another Member State.
It is a condition that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT for these services, a obligation that arises from Council Directive 2008 / 8 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC concerning the location of the service.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of the data of the VAT pre-registration and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data This recommendation related to the German financial administration.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech financial administration automatically balances the data on intra-Community transactions from the VAT declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of the VAT is an essential prerequisite for the proper functioning of the EU internal market.
Therefore, the fight against VAT fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The significance of this is confirmed, among other things, by a study published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In it, an external expert estimated the loss of VAT for the 25 Member States in the period 2000 to 2006. According to analysis of the available data, the tax loss for that period was between 90 and 113 billion Euros, based on the assumption that the EU-25 lose on average 12% of the turnover taxes due to them each year.
The estimated 0th tax loss for the CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first assessment found that a Member State cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS) on its own.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
Regarding the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (Eurocanet).
For this purpose, intra-EU transactions at high risk, carried out by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in Eurocanet, were selected (see chapter 4.3).
The aim of the EUROFISC network is to optimise mutual assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively, and to improve cooperation between the competent authorities in order to detect cases of fraud as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to estimate the risk potential of intra-Community transactions.
The ECOFIN Council approved EUROFISC on 7 October 2008 and at the same time adopted the principles for the operation of the system.
Eurocanet, developed by the Belgian financial administration in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7, serves as a model for EUROFISC.
The purpose of the system is to detect high-risk transactions and identify entrepreneurs involved in organised fraud.
