4.2 Control of selected intra-Community transactions
The first audit looked together at transactions where there were doubts as to whether they had actually been carried out or whether discrepancies had been detected in the reports of taxpayers in both Member States.
For the audit, the two courts of auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community supply of goods between the CZ and Germany, where the tax assessment by the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint audit.
(1)
A Czech taxable person purchased goods worth 22 686 euros from a German taxable person in the first quarter of 2005.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his VAT declaration, since the period mentioned in the German tax bill did not have a VAT identification number, but only a tax number for intra-German transactions.
Through international mutual assistance in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that, according to German VAT law, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not require a VAT identification number in order to benefit from the exemption of intra-Community supplies of goods.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that, according to the audit carried out by the competent Czech FA, the Czech taxable person submitted an additional VAT declaration declaring the purchase of goods in the above-mentioned value, while at the same time claiming the same amount of VAT deductions.
(2)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxable person was reported to have purchased goods worth 12 561 euros from a German taxable person.
However, he said he had not purchased the goods and therefore did not declare it in his UST statement.
The German financial administration refused to process the request, citing a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, because the turnover associated with the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of 15,000 euros.
Since the Czech FA was not able to obtain documents, the tax audit remained unsuccessful and the original tax determination was maintained.
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech FA from Germany received two spontaneous reports in accordance with the Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, according to which the German taxpayer had invoiced the delivery of the goods in question to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech taxpayer purchased the goods from the Slovak taxable person and indicated the acquisition in his regular VAT statement for the month of October 2004.
(3)
A Czech taxable person is alleged to have purchased a car worth 48 500 euros from a German taxable person in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he did not declare any intra-Community acquisition.
In addition, he had not made a UST statement since August 2004, which is why the FA set the VAT at CZK 0 for the quarter in question.
On the basis of information received from Germany in the course of the international exchange of information in accordance with the Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the FA requested the taxable person in March 2007 to submit a subsequent tax declaration, which the taxpayer omitted.
The audit found that the FA had carried out further audit work in this tax case in 2007, when it found that the car in question had been sold by the taxpayer to a used car dealer in the CZ.
The Czech FA carried out an assessment for the December 2004 tax period, setting additional taxes of CZK 295 379 for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The competent Czech court decided to open insolvency proceedings on the assets of the Czech taxable person; an insolvency administrator was appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax debt is likely to be unrecoverable.
4) Moonlight
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxable person was reported to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) with a total value of 198 167 euros to Germany.
In response to a request for information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, it was stated that a tax penalty procedure was pending against the German taxpayer in Germany.
The audit by the Federal Audit Office showed that after the conclusion of the proceedings there was evidence of the involvement of the German taxpayer in fraud.
The intra-Community acquisition of goods was subjected to employment taxation amounting to 182 424 Euro (for 2004) and 369 690 Euro (for 2005).
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech taxpayer was involved in carousel fraud involving new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German financial administration, a VAT audit of the Czech taxpayer took place for the tax periods of April, May and June 2005.
Based on the test findings and information from the international exchange of information, the FA set additional VAT at 703 031 CZK for May 2005 and 726 551 CZK for June 2005.
5) Moonlight
Czech taxable person A is alleged to have purchased a machine with a total value of 58 000 Euros from a German taxpayer in February 2005.
In the third quarter of 2004, the German taxable person was alleged to have delivered a machine valued at 88 027 euros to the Czech tax payer B. B, however, denied the acquisition.
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that B had purchased the machine from a German company with a branch in the CZ.
Czech taxable person A did not specify the purchase of the goods from the said German taxpayer in his declaration of VAT.
The German FA's response to a request for information in accordance with the Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 showed that the German taxpayer had not made an intra-Community delivery of a machine with a value of 58 000 Euros, but had made a delivery within the CZ.
In the audit, the Federal Audit Office found that the intra-Community delivery of the machine after completion of an audit was classified as domestic delivery and the VAT exemption was subsequently refused.
6) Mourinho
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxable person was reported to have delivered to a Czech taxable person goods worth 11 600 euros.
The goods were purchased and later sold in Germany, i.e. in 2005.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA had established its predisposition on the basis of a supplementary VAT declaration, which prohibited purchases from another Member State, including purchases in the above-mentioned amount.
The Federal Audit Office found that after receiving a reply to a request for information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the German FA corrected the VAT declaration of the German taxpayer and set an additional VAT of 1,600 euros.
Due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding UST predisposition there, an audit is under way.
The ZM of the German taxable person has not yet been corrected, since in Germany only the taxable person who has surrendered the ZM can correct it.
7) Beyonce
The competent Czech FA received a request for information from the German financial administration in accordance with the Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the question of the acquisition of a car worth 47 400 euros by a Czech taxpayer in February 2005.
After a review for the 2005 tax period, the Czech FA set the tax debt of the Czech taxable person at CZK 0 and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the acquisition of the car by the Czech taxpayer.
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the registration of the Czech VAT collector had been cancelled because he had not complied with his tax obligations.
The Czech FA sent the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxpayer has not so far corrected his information in the ZM, but has appealed against the tax ruling.
8) Moonlight
According to MIAS10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxable person supplied a Czech taxable person with a total value of 33 205 euros, which he did not declare as an intra-Community acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA investigated the reasons for the discrepancies.
For the first quarter of 2005, the Czech taxable person repeatedly made subsequent VAT declarations.
However, the Czech FA was unable to clarify the difference between the purchases of CZK 134 273 in the period from the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005, based on the fact that sales for individual quarters could not be accurately allocated, and accepted the UST declarations made.
9) Beyonce
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxable person had delivered to a Czech taxable person goods worth 46 854 euros.
For the same period, the Czech taxpayer declared the intra-Community purchase of goods worth only 14,856 euros.
As part of the interstate exchange of information in accordance with the Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the Czech FA reviewed the actual value of the delivery.
With the German answer to this request, three invoices were sent, which showed a total value of the delivered goods of 31,998 euros, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the acquisition declared by the Czech taxpayer and the MIAS data.
According to the results of the audit by the Czech Court of Auditors, following repeated warnings from the FA, the Czech taxpayer submitted a subsequent VAT declaration in January 2007 for the tax period of July 2004.
With this declaration, the taxable person made his claim for deduction at the same time. Therefore, his tax debt for the respective tax period remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures for the transactions selected for the audit had been completed and that the financial administrations in the CZ or Germany had taken appropriate measures (e.g. subsequent VAT requirements or prevention of pre-tax refunds).
4.3 Testing of selected cases of risk-related intra-Community transactions
4.3.1 Findings in the Czech Republic
Eurocanet can be an important source of information to identify high-risk taxpayers in the acquisition Member State.
In the CZ, the early warning information obtained from Eurocanet is checked by the competent FA with the purchasers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, the CZ has provided information on turnover and taxable suppliers, which are considered at risk, to the Eurocanet system.
Nine Czech taxpayers were selected for the audit,
Entered into the Eurocanet by the financial administrations of other Member States, either as suppliers or purchasers.
