Since the German financial administration did not participate in the data exchange via Eurocanet, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with German VAT identification numbers were considered risky by the German financial administration.
The audit found both normal transactions and those suspected of carousel fraud or other fraud.
In the cases concerned, the parties exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003,
For example:
• In the examination of the early warning information, the Fähr did not identify any suspicions of risky transactions.
The taxpayers in question were constantly monitored because their data was stored in Eurocanet.
• In the checks of the high-risk transactions, the companies failed to prove breaches of the rules for calculating the tax base and the VAT on the basis of the accounting documents submitted, even though they detected discrepancies in the transport and storage of the goods or discovered business relations with mail order companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual business transactions was complicated because certain taxpayers did not cooperate with the tax authorities and could not be contacted.
The competent authorities reviewed most of the high-risk taxable persons and transactions mentioned in Eurocanet's early warning messages.
However, their options for checking risk-related transactions, especially so-called "missing traders," are limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly prove the fraudulent behaviour of the taxable person.
Tougher registration requirements for taxable persons for VAT purposes and greater flexibility in deleting registrations would help to combat VAT fraud.
The taxable persons involved in fraudulent carousel transactions can be registered for the purposes of the VAT, in order to deceive fictitious goods deliveries throughout the EU or formally issue correct tax receipts to other taxpayers, with which they can then make unauthorized claims for deduction of VAT.
In case of suspected carousel fraud in connection with imports and exports, it is recommended that the customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to be able to monitor the legality of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final buyer.
