4.4 Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
4.4.1 Interstate assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
The legislation on intergovernmental assistance to recover certain claims in the EU is essentially based on:
- Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures which form part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, as well as levies and tariffs;
Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC amending Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures which form part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, as well as exhaustion and customs duties and VAT and certain excise duties; and
Commission Directive 2002 / 94 / EC laying down detailed rules for the implementation of certain articles of Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to certain duties, duties, taxes and other measures.
The CZ implemented Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC by Law No. 252 / 2000 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims.
Following the adoption of Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC, it was also necessary to transpose it into Czech law, and at the same time to amend the aforementioned law.
In this context, Amendment No 191 / 2004 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims has been adopted.
A new significant piece of legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179 / 2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009. Furthermore, the regulation makes electronic transmission mandatory and requires the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all documents sent to the respective original.
The main principles of international mutual assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. The principle of reciprocity applies;
2. Mutual assistance is to be provided only on request and if all conditions are fulfilled;
3. Mutual assistance does not extend to claims that are considered a criminal sanction in the requested State;
4. The procedure of intergovernmental assistance for recovery of claims must be carried out in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. Foreign claims do not take precedence over domestic claims in the accession procedure;
6. Mutual assistance is provided only for the recovery of undisputed claims;
7. The principle of utilization applies: The requesting State must use all the means available to it under national law to recover the claim.
Law No 191 / 2004 provides for three forms of mutual assistance: The issuing of information, the notification of legal acts and the actual recovery.
